"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989536","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Government, the EA and the HSE have taken appropriate steps to ensure that a regulatory scheme for chemicals will be ready before the UK leaves the EU in 2019.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-10-24T13:21:52.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989536/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989536/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-17","European Chemicals Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment he has made of the capacity of  (a) his Department and (b) agencies of his Department to replicate the functions of the European Chemicals Agency in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","180708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989537","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-22","<p>The Highway Code provides guidance for drivers on being aware of cyclists and other vulnerable road users and allowing adequate distance when passing them.</p><p>The Department is aware that not all road users follow the rules on safe overtaking and on 18 October 2018 the Department that the Highway Code will be reviewed to help keep cyclists, vulnerable road users and pedestrians safe on the roads.</p><p>This followed announcements in the summer committing to update the Highway Code in relation to close passing and highlighting a UK-wide initiative to help police enforce against dangerous drivers who pass cyclists too closely.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-10-22T16:21:24.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989537/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989537/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-17","Dangerous Driving","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to increase driver awareness of the dangers of overtaking (a) cyclists and (b) other vulnerable road users without leaving sufficient space.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","180667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989538","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-22","<p>The Department has used the ‘Innovation Challenge Fund’ to assess how new technologies such as virtual reality can help learner drivers to develop their hazard perception skills prior to taking their tests.</p><p> </p><p>Virtual reality road safety awareness films are likely to be helpful in driver education. They promise to bring an added spatial dimension to the experience and can be very engaging when used well. It is important that they should always be based on the kinds of established behavioural change techniques used by the THINK! Campaign, the best local authority driver education, and the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","180669","2018-10-22T10:28:52.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989538/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989538/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-17","Driving Instruction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on the inclusion in driver education on road safety of up-to-date visual tools and materials, including virtual reality films, to ensure that people are made aware of their driving from the perspective of other road users.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","180668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989539","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-22","<p>The Department has used the ‘Innovation Challenge Fund’ to assess how new technologies such as virtual reality can help learner drivers to develop their hazard perception skills prior to taking their tests.</p><p> </p><p>Virtual reality road safety awareness films are likely to be helpful in driver education. They promise to bring an added spatial dimension to the experience and can be very engaging when used well. It is important that they should always be based on the kinds of established behavioural change techniques used by the THINK! Campaign, the best local authority driver education, and the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","180668","2018-10-22T10:28:52.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989539/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989539/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-17","Driving Instruction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the merits of promoting virtual reality road safety awareness films as an educational tool for drivers.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","180669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989540","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-10-24","<p>As set out in the Government’s White Paper on the future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union we are aiming for a UK-EU free trade area on goods, including chemicals, to ensure trade is as free and frictionless as possible. We are seeking participation in the European Chemical Agency, accepting its rules including the REACH Regulation and contributing to its costs.</p><p>As part of this, we would be seeking to secure access to relevant IT systems and data. This approach will enable us to meet our objective of ensuring that chemicals only need to be approved once in either market and ensure that UK businesses can continue to register chemical substances directly, rather than working through an EU-based representative.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-10-24T10:45:36.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989540/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989540/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-17","Chemicals: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of continued participation in the EU Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals programme in (a) any withdrawal agreement with the EU and (b) the event that the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","180709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989541","Home Office","false","2018-10-26","<p>The National Police Air Service (NPAS) is a collaboration of police forces. The level of financial contribution made by individual forces to the service is a matter for Police and Crime Commissioners and the NPAS Strategic Board.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-10-26T13:21:27.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989541/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989541/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-17","National Police Air Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what representations he has received from the National Police Air Service on force contributions to that Service.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","180820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989542","Treasury","false","2018-10-22","<p>Between the introduction of the Help to Buy ISA in December 2015 to March 2018, the average property purchase price in Oxfordshire under the scheme was £196,618. This is based upon 624 property purchase completions taking place, with a total expected value of c.£122.7 million. The information is recorded and published in the Help to Buy ISA Quarterly Statistics accompanying tables. The last release of these was 16<sup>th</sup> August 2018, which can be found using the following link - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/help-to-buy-isa-scheme-quarterly-statistics-december-2015-to-31-march-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/help-to-buy-isa-scheme-quarterly-statistics-december-2015-to-31-march-2018</a></p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-10-22T16:26:36.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989542/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989542/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-17","Help to Buy Scheme: Oxfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2018 to Question 176641 on help to buy scheme: Oxfordshire, if he will (a) publish and (b) place in the Library the calculation relating to the average value of a property completion under that scheme in Oxfordshire.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","180848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989543","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-29","<p>UK-contracted personnel, including UK military personnel on secondment to BAE Systems, support the safe storage and issue of weapons from their place of storage to an end user, in accordance with long-standing government-to-government arrangements.</p><p>They do not load weapons for operations in Yemen, nor are they involved in the planning of operational sorties.</p><p>The UK Government operates one of the most robust arms export control regimes in the world.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-10-29T16:46:54.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989543/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989543/answer","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989543/answer/previousversion/81201","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether restrictions have been placed on the work of Saudi-based UK (a) military personnel and (b) private contractors to his Department, in relation to the (i) preparation, (ii) maintenance and (iii) operational use of air-delivered weapons used in the conflict in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989544","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-31","<p>Military personnel, wherever they are serving, would be expected to report any concerns about possible violations of international humanitarian law through submissions to their chain of command.</p><p>We expect any UK-contractors providing support under the Saudi Armed Forces Projects who might witness or otherwise receive information on violations of international humanitarian law to report it through their companies.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-10-31T15:55:18.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989544/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989544/answer","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989544/answer/previousversion/81205","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Saudi Arabia: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what guidance the Government provides to (a) Saudi-based UK military personnel and (b) private contractors to the MoD under Saudi armed forces project on reporting suspicions of violations of international humanitarian law.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989545","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-30","<p>The previously proposed Modern Dock Hall, referred to colloquially as the 'Frigate Factory', was thoroughly investigated by BAE Systems but ultimately they concluded that the cost and level of associated risk did not represent value for money. The Ministry of Defence was consulted and agreed with their conclusion.</p><p>The National Shipbuilding Strategy was clear that all Royal Navy warships will be built and integrated in the UK. The Type 26 frigates are being built on the Clyde, securing a total of 4,000 jobs across the UK supply chain and 20 years of work. Since 2010 this Government has invested more than £6 billion in shipbuilding in the UK, securing thousands of jobs. In 2018-19 we expect to spend in excess of £750 million supporting the fleet.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-10-30T15:18:55.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989545/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989545/answer","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989545/answer/previousversion/81206","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Shipbuilding: River Clyde","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Government plans to support the construction of a frigate factory on the River Clyde.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989546","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-23","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) keeps the security of UK waters in the North Atlantic under constant review, we consider the activity of both state and non-state actors. I shall not go into further detail for reasons of safeguarding national security. As part of NATO the MOD and the Royal Navy work seamlessly with Allies to keep our waters safe and secure.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-10-23T14:02:04.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989546/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989546/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Territorial Waters: North Atlantic Ocean","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the security of UK waters in the North Atlantic.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989547","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-29","<p>The Ministry of Defence continues to work closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) and other Government Departments to ensure that we can address the implications and realise the opportunities of the UK's withdrawal from the EU, including the effect on our Armed Forces.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","181294","2018-10-29T16:52:34.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989547/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989547/answer","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989547/answer/previousversion/81213","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what preparations his Department has made for the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989548","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-29","<p>Quality accommodation is very important for Defence and a key enabler of operational capability. The Ministry of Defence continues to make improvements to the Service Family Accommodation (SFA) and Single Living Accommodation (SLA) estate.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to routine maintenance, we have invested in improving energy efficiency through the provision of new boilers, doors and windows, roofs, and external wall insulation.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, we have installed thousands of new kitchens and bathrooms to provide our Armed Forces and their families with modern facilities. The number of properties that meet the Government Decent Homes standard has increased significantly and now sits at more than 95% of our total stock.</p><p> </p><p>The Single Living Accommodation Modernisation project, has been one of the largest new build and refurbishment projects in the UK and has delivered successful renovations and constructions on 52 locations from Scotland to Cornwall over the last 15 years with over £1.2 billion invested; and we continue to invest in both of these areas.</p><p> </p><p>In parallel, we are developing new accommodation options for service personnel through the Future Accommodation Model programme.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-10-29T16:49:53.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989548/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989548/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989548/answer/previousversion/81207","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps the Government is taking to improve (a) housing and (b) lodgings for armed forces personnel.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989549","Cabinet Office","false","2018-10-23","<p>The 2016 National Cyber Security Strategy sets out in detail the Government’s approach to improve the UK’s cyber security. This includes a wide range of measures to defend our people, deter our adversaries and develop the capabilities we need to ensure the UK remains the safest place to live and do business online.</p><p> </p><p>One of the most visible elements of the strategy is the creation of the National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC), to improve our prevention and response capability and ensure that citizens and business have the best advice on how to protect themselves. For more on their role, the NCSC’s second Annual Review can be found at https://www.ncsc.gov.uk/news/annual-review-2018.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-10-23T13:44:33.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989549/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989549/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-10-17","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to improve the UK’s cyber security.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989550","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-22","<p>It is not always possible to track actual expenditure on specific services against all funds allocated for those services. However, we can confirm that the clinical commissioning group spend on children and young people’s mental health has increased, rising from £516 million in 2015/16, to £619 million in 2016/17 and to £687 million in 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England and NHS Improvement’s Operational Planning and Contracting Guidance 2017-2019 makes it clear that additional transformation funding for mental health care made available to support the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health should “not be used to supplant existing spend or balance reductions elsewhere”.</p><p> </p><p>This requirement applies to deliverables for improved children and young people’s mental health services as well as for adult services.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2018-10-22T16:50:09.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989550/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989550/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that clinical commissioning groups spend funds allocated for children and young people’s mental health services on those services.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","180711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989551","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-22","<p>Although some relevant data on staff roles is available on the National Health Service Electronic Staff Record, this does not currently align with the staff groups targeted for growth within the mental health workforce plan.</p><p> </p><p>Because the Department is keen to track progress with implementation of the plan we asked Health Education England (HEE) to develop a Mental Health Workforce Dashboard to monitor plans for the delivery of the workforce targets. This uses:</p><p>- Data from Strategic Transformation Partnership regional plans (to monitor staff expansion plans);</p><p>- NHS Digital data to track the size of the whole mental health workforce;</p><p>- Data from NHS Improvement on staff retention rates; and</p><p>- Data from HEE on the numbers of trainee staff currently studying and those undertaking specific courses for upskilling themselves to work in mental health.</p><p> </p><p>For the longer term a project is underway, led by the Department, to improve the way in which NHS Digital data captures changes in workforce numbers. We are hoping that this will enable more accurate reporting of actual staff changes from early next financial year.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2018-10-22T16:28:50.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989551/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989551/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to paragraph 2.16 of the National Audit Office report, Improving children and young people’s mental health services, published on 9 October 2018, what assessment he has made of the effect on his Department's ability to measure the expansion of NHS workforce against sustainability and transformation plans of Health Education England not expecting to have data on the number of NHS staff working in children and young people’s services until 2019.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","180712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989552","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-22","<p>Health Education England (HEE) has established a Mental Health Workforce Delivery Group attended by the Department and its arm’s length bodies. The group oversees implementation of the workforce plan through regional Sustainability and Transformation Partnerships (STPs).</p><p> </p><p>HEE have introduced an online resource for their regional leads in support of workforce planning, called ‘Recipe for good workforce planning’. This includes a ‘confirm and challenge’ process whereby HEE Regional Leads work closely with STP partners to ensure that workforce growth is happening according to STP delivery plans. Regional leads challenge where plans for staff expansion fall short of those required by ‘Stepping Forward’ and ensure that plans are in place to mitigate risks. NHS England is also holding quarterly ‘deep dives’ with all the regional teams to review progress against provider and STP level plans.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2018-10-22T16:39:25.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989552/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989552/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to paragraph 14 on page 9 of the National Audit Office report, Improving children and young people's mental health services, published on 9 October 2018, what steps he is taking to recruit additional NHS staff to work in those services.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","180713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989553","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-23","<p>Good progress has been made on the Modernising Defence Programme and I expect to be in a position to share the results later in the autumn.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","180809","2018-10-23T14:02:42.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989553/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989553/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Defence: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his spending priorities are for the modernising defence programme are.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989554","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-23","<p>Good progress has been made on the Modernising Defence Programme and I expect to be in a position to share the results later in the autumn.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson","180808","2018-10-23T14:02:42.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989554/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989554/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Defence: Modernisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent progress he has made on the (a) development and (b) implementation of the modernising defence programme.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989555","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-29","<p>Regular Armed Forces personnel may become members of civilian trade unions and political parties. Armed Forces personnel are however not permitted to participate in industrial action or take any active part in the affairs of political organisation, party or movement. Personnel are expected to abide by Queen's Regulations and act in accordance with Service values and standards.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-10-29T16:48:38.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989555/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989555/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989555/answer/previousversion/81208","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-17","Armed Forces: Political Parties and Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will review his Department's policy on the right of armed forces personnel to join a (a) trades union and (b) political party.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","180810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989556","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-22","<p>The Department has made no specific assessment of the effect of medical nutrition, also known as the ketogenic diet, on the management of drug-resistant epilepsy. However, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence sets out best practice guidance for clinicians in ‘Epilepsies: diagnosis and management’ which is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg137" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg137</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-22T16:09:55.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989556/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989556/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Epilepsy: Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the effect of medical nutrition on the management of drug-resistant epilepsy.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","180714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989557","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-22","<p>The Director General of the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) reported in detail on 16 April and again on 18 April to the Executive Council meeting of the OPCW about the attempted deployment of the Fact Finding Mission to Douma. The UK is a member of the Executive Council and was represented at both meetings. The OPCW Director General's relevant statements to the Executive Council are available on the website of the OPCW.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-22T16:31:47.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989557/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989557/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-17","Syria: Chemical Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 17 September 2018 to Question 172062 on Syria: chemical weapons, what the evidential basis is for his statement that the Director General of the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons reported that they had been prevented from deploying to Douma by Russia and Syria.","false","Biography information for Chris Williamson","Derby North","Chris Williamson","180699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989558","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-10-24","<p>The 3.3 kilotonnes of PM2.5 emissions from domestic burning of coal is based on the figure of 361.88 kilotonnes, taken from the 2016 Digest of United Kingdom Energy Statistics.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-10-24T10:58:24.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989558/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989558/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-17","Coal","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2018 to Question 176140 on coal, what tonnage of house coal was the calculation based on that 3.3 kilotonnes of PM2.5 emissions were produced by burning house coal in the UK in 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","180678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989559","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-10-24","<p>My officials have met a variety of stakeholders including a range of fuel suppliers, chimney sweeps and other interested parties over the past year to develop proposals for reducing the impact of domestic burning on air quality. This has included meetings with coal merchants in April and wood suppliers in October. They met CPL in bilateral meetings in January, March and April this year. Ministers have not met CPL over the past year.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-10-24T10:09:55.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989559/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989559/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-17","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: CPL Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what meetings (a) he (b) his Ministers and (c) his officials have had with CPL Ltd over the last year; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","180679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989560","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-10-24","<p>No Defra Ministers or officials have met the Competitions and Markets Authority on CPL Ltd in the last 12 months.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-10-24T09:55:50.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989560/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989560/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-17","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Competition and Markets Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what meetings (a) he, (b) Ministers in his department and (c) officials in his department, have had with the Competition and Markets Authority on CPL Ltd in the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","180680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989561","Department for International Development","false","2018-10-24","<p>UK Official Development Assistance (ODA) data is collected and reported according to a standard international classification produced by the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD). Following this classification, the amount of UK ODA delivered by UK and other donor country NGOs in the last five years[1] is:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Net ODA</p></td><td><p>£488m</p></td><td><p>£662m</p></td><td><p>£759m</p></td><td><p>£772m</p></td><td><p>£710m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The latest data is for calendar year 2016 and figures for 2017 will be published this autumn.</p><p>ODA flows are provided by official agencies and their executive agencies. The amount of UK ODA provided by the Welsh Government and delivered by donor-based NGOs is:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Net ODA</p></td><td><p>£1m</p></td><td><p>£1m</p></td><td><p>£1m</p></td><td><p>£1m</p></td><td><p>£1m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: Statistics on International Development</p><p>The information for (b) is not held in the form requested and can only be collated at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Donor-based NGOs cover UK based NGOs as well as the NGOs of other donors. The figures included above will mainly consist of UK based NGOs however there are some amounts included for other donor NGOs delivering UK ODA, such as UK contributions to the Norway-based, Norwegian Refugee Council.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-10-24T15:47:55.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989561/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989561/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-17","Overseas Aid: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the amount of funding allocated to UK-based organisations spent on (a) overseas aid and (b) administrative costs within Wales in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","180844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989562","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-22","<p>Since 2011 the Department has provided more than £26 million in financial support to NHS Blood and Transplant (NHSBT) and Anthony Nolan to enable improved provision of stem cells for patients requiring a transplant, supporting the recruitment and management of donors.</p><p> </p><p>Departmental funding has also enabled the establishment of a unified stem cell registry for the United Kingdom, the ‘Anthony Nolan and the NHS Stem Cell Registry’. There are now 1.4 million potential donors on the UK’s aligned registry.</p><p> </p><p>Each of the UK’s stem cell registries that collectively form the ‘Anthony Nolan and the NHS Stem Cell Registry’ is a member of the World Marrow Donor Association (WMDA) – a group of organisations and individuals who promote global collaboration and best practices for the benefit of stem cell donors and transplant patients.</p><p> </p><p>The WMDA’s ‘Search and Match Service’ is a global database of life-saving donors that provides a fast search facility to find the best matched donor or cord blood unit in the world for a patient in need of a blood stem cell transplant.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2018-10-22T16:49:07.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989562/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989562/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Stem Cells: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that adequate numbers of donors are available for patients requiring a stem cell transplant.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","180770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989563","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-22","<p>This information is not held centrally. As with many NHS services, the funding and commissioning of palliative and end of life care is a local matter, over which individual National Health Service commissioners have responsibility.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-10-22T16:11:47.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989563/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989563/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Hospices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much statutory funding each Clinical Commissioning Group in England provided to hospices in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","180771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989564","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-26","<p>HMP Berwyn in Wrexham, North Wales opened on 27 February 2017, and when fully operational, will create 2,106 modern and efficient prison places holding category C men. The latest data for Berwyn (published September 2018) shows a population of just over 1170 and is currently ramping up its population as part of its safe mobilisation.</p><p> </p><p>When the prison is at full capacity it will be the largest prison in the UK therefore the ramp up of population needs to affiliate with the continual recruitment, training and attrition of staff and the number of purposeful activity spaces available. This is paramount to provide an environment safe for those who work and reside within the prison whilst delivering a rehabilitative purpose.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-10-26T13:27:58.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989564/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989564/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-17","Berwyn Prison","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 17 September 2018 to Question 171712, if he will publish his Department's plan for bringing HMP Berwyn up to full capacity.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","180831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989565","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-10-22","<p>The Gambling Commission has advised me that it undertook enhanced and significant due diligence in relation to Mr Melnik’s Park Lane Club casino licence application in 2014. Based on the result of those checks it was satisfied as to his suitability to be associated with the licence. The Gambling Commission is currently reviewing Silverbond’s (Park Lane Casino’s) licence to provide gambling in Britain.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Details of the Commission’s processes may be found at the following links:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>https://www.gamblingcommission.gov.uk/for-gambling-businesses/Apply-for-a-licence/What-you-need-to-send-us-when-you-apply-for-an-operating-licence-medium-to-large-businesses.aspx</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gamblingcommission.gov.uk/PDF/Statement-of-principles-for-licensing-and-regulation.pdf</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gamblingcommission.gov.uk/news-action-and-statistics/Regulatory-action/Review-a-licence.aspx</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-10-22T14:10:22.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989565/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989565/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-17","Vasilijs Melniks ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether the Gambling Commission undertook due diligence on Vasilijs Melniks before granting a licence to the Park Lane Casino in London.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","180723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989566","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-22","<p>Information about the volumes and outcomes of appeals - including (i) Personal Independence Payment (PIP) and (ii) Employment Support Allowance (ESA) - to the First-tier Tribunal (Social Security and Child Support) (SSCS) is published at:</p><p>www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics</p><p> </p><p>Since PIP was introduced 3.5m decisions have been made up to June 2018, of these 9% have been appealed and 4% have been overturned.</p><p> </p><p>Between April 2014 – March 2018, 3.5m ESA (post Work Capability Assessment) decisions have been made, of these 8% have been appealed and 4% have been overturned.</p><p> </p><p>SSCS appeals are listed into the hearing venue nearest to the appellant’s home address. The published csv files (which can be viewed at the link above) provide information about the outcomes of PIP and ESA appeals for hearing venues covering (a) Coventry, (b) the West Midlands and (c) England for the period April to June 2018, the latest period for which data are available.</p><p>The table below contains the requested information for (iii) Income Support (IS), (iv) Job Seekers Allowance (JSA), (v) Tax Credits and (vi) Universal Credit (UC):</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Proportion<sup>1</sup> of appeals decided in favour of the appellant for the period April to June 2018 (the latest period for which data are available)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>IS</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>JSA</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Tax Credits<sup>2</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UC</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Coventry </strong></p></td><td><p>43%</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>~</p></td><td><p>71%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>West Midlands<sup>3</sup></strong></p></td><td><p>27%</p></td><td><p>23%</p></td><td><p>27%</p></td><td><p>50%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>England<sup>4</sup></strong></p></td><td><p>38%</p></td><td><p>34%</p></td><td><p>32%</p></td><td><p>54%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><ol><li>Proportion based on the number of cases found in favour of the appellant at a tribunal hearing, as a percentage of the cases heard at a tribunal hearing</li><li>Includes Working Family Tax Credit, Child Tax Credit, and Working Tax Credit.</li><li>West Midlands includes the venues: Birmingham, Wolverhampton, Walsall, Coventry, Nuneaton, Stoke, Telford, Hereford and Worcester.</li><li>Excludes SSCS Scotland Region and Wales Region.</li></ol><p>~ Equates to value lower than 5</p><p>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-</p><p>scale case management system and are the best data that are available.</p><p>These data may differ slightly from that of the published statistics as these data were run on a different date.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-11-22T16:20:23.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989566/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989566/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-17","Employment Tribunals Service: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of appeals to the tribunals service in (a) Coventry, (b) the West Midlands and (c) England which related to (i) personal independence payments, (ii) employment and support allowance, (iii) income support, (iv) jobseeker's allowance and (v) tax credits, (vi) universal credit were successful in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Colleen Fletcher","Coventry North East","Colleen Fletcher","180772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989567","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-22","<p>HM Prison and Probation workforce statistics detailing staffing by establishment are published quarterly. The latest publication can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/her-majestys-prison-and-probation-service-workforce-quarterly-march-2018</p><p> </p><p>Prison officer numbers are at their highest in five years, which is vital to ensuring prisons are safe, secure and decent. We now have over 3,500 additional staff in post compared to October 2016. The recruitment drive will continue until we reach required levels across the prison estate, ensuring prisons can fulfil their purpose - protecting the public, reducing reoffending and crucially, rehabilitating offenders. Increased staff numbers will enable us to implement the key worker role, giving staff dedicated time to provide one-to-one support to individual prisoners and, for example, identify where mental health support may be needed.</p><p> </p><p>Staffing for prison healthcare services at HMP Risley is a matter for healthcare providers under contract to NHS England. Prison governors work collaboratively with NHS England commissioners to support the commissioning of high quality healthcare services across the prison estate in England.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-10-22T16:48:11.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989567/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989567/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-17","Risley Prison: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make an assessment of the adequacy of the number of (a) prison officers and (b) qualified mental health practitioners employed at HMP Risley.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","180643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989568","Department for International Development","false","2018-10-22","<p>The UK has been a leading donor in responding to the Rohingya crisis; since August 2017 we have committed £129m. The needs of women and girls are a key consideration of all our programming</p><p> </p><p>This support has already delivered toilets and hygiene facilities for over one million people and emergency latrines for over 280,000 people. This includes the construction of 53 latrines and bathing spaces that are segregated for women and girls and have lights installed for their safety. Recent allocations to partners, including Christian Aid, UNICEF and UNHCR, will support additional latrines, tube wells, water points and bathing cubicles and 14 women friendly spaces with washing and sanitation facilities.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-10-22T14:43:40.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989568/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989568/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-17","Bangladesh: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding her Department has allocated to provision of secure and properly screened toilets for Rohingya women refugees in Bangladesh in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","180644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989569","Department for Education","false","2018-10-22","<p>In selecting a preferred sponsor for University Academy Warrington, the Regional Schools Commissioner for Lancashire and West Yorkshire will consider the trust’s track record of working with pupils who have similar characteristics to those at University Academy Warrington, alongside a range of other criteria, including the raising of attainment.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-10-22T16:47:55.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989569/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989569/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-17","University Academy Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to ensure that the new provider for University Academy Warrington has (a) expertise in and (b) a track record of raising the attainment of working class pupils; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","180645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989570","Home Office","false","2018-10-22","<p>Reserves are an important tool for police leaders, but this is taxpayers’ money and we need real transparency about how it is being used.</p><p>That is why in January the Government published information on police reserves and provided guidance to Police and Crime Commissioners making clear that they must be more open with taxpayers about their plans to use them.</p><p>The exact level of reserves is a matter for individual Police and Crime Commissioners, who have a legal duty to set balanced annual budgets and ensure they have adequate reserves. Police reserve levels since 2011 are published in the Police Financial Reserves section on gov.uk. These can be found by following the link below. Earlier figures can be found in former Police Authority statements of accounts.</p><p>We will shortly be publishing March 2018 police reserve figures on gov.uk, following the publication of Police and Crime Commissioners’ annual accounts</p><p><br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-financial-reserves" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-financial-reserves</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-10-22T16:46:10.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989570/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989570/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-17","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what level of reserve funding police forces held at 31 March in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","180737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989571","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-22","<p>The general practitioner (GP) Contract and the ‘Directed Enhanced Service Specification; Seasonal influenza and pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccination programme 2018/19’ describes the service that GPs should offer. GPs are expected to proactively call eligible patients for vaccination and also to recall them if they are defined as at risk due to an underlying medical condition.</p><p> </p><p>During each season, NHS England teams take all opportunities in their communication with practices to reinforce this requirement, and Public Health England have made available resources to encourage GPs to promote flu vaccination.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-22T16:20:21.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989571/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989571/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Influenza: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will take steps to ensure that GPs contact patients who are entitled to a free flu vaccination invite those patients to be vaccinated.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","180646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989572","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-25","<p>The national ‘Help us help you: stay well this winter’ campaign promotes uptake of the flu vaccination and was launched on 8 October 2018. It will run until 17 December 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Activity includes television, radio, social and digital advertising, supported by search, partnership activity and public relations.</p><p> </p><p>The first phase highlights the seriousness of flu for at-risk groups and how vaccination offers the best protection. Public Health England advice is to speak to a general practitioner (GP), pharmacist or midwife.</p><p> </p><p>This message is replicated across all advertising materials, including those for partners, with a minor variation in communications concerning flu vaccination for children. Children aged two and three are vaccinated by GPs and children in reception to year five are vaccinated at school.</p><p> </p><p>The second phase encourages at-risk groups to get their flu vaccination and visit a pharmacist at the first sign of a winter illness.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-25T12:00:57.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989572/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989572/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Influenza: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that people who are entitled to a free flu vaccination are aware that the vaccination can be obtained from pharmacies as well as from GP surgeries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","180647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989573","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>We are committed to securing a deal that works for the entire United Kingdom - for Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland and England. The Department for Exiting the European Union and the Department of Health and Social Care regularly engage with the devolved administrations to update them on the negotiations.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-10-24T12:50:00.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989573/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989573/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Health Services: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effect on the health and social care sectors in each nation of the UK of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","180759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989574","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>Department for Exiting the European Union and Department of Health and Social Care Ministers speak regularly with Ministers from the Scottish and Welsh governments to update them on the negotiations, including through the Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations. Close cooperation between the United Kingdom Government and the devolved administrations remains essential to delivering an exit that works for all parts of the UK.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-10-24T12:47:24.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989574/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989574/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Health Services: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent discussions he has had with Ministers in each of the devolved administrations on his Department's assessment of the effect on the health and social care sector in each nation of the UK of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","180760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989575","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-22","<p>Data on the proportion of people eligible for a free flu vaccination that have received vaccine in each of the last five years is available in the attached table.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-10-22T16:23:26.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989575/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989575/answer","Copy of PQ180648_VaccineUptake_Past5yearsAmended.xlsx","PQ180648 attached document","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989575/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Influenza: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what proportion of people eligible for free flu vaccination have received that vaccine in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","180648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989576","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Department has regular conversations with health and social care providers as well as with the devolved administrations to ensure an exit is delivered which works for the health and social care sector throughout the entire United Kingdom.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-10-24T12:58:23.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989576/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989576/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Health Services: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department consulted health and social care service providers on the effect on those sectors (a) throughout the UK and (b) in each of the four nations of the UK of leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","180761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989577","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>The UK was one of the first of over 100 countries to recognise Kosovo’s statehood. We support Kosovo's integration into the international rules-based system through membership of international organisations, which can help promote stability and prosperity; for example, we support Kosovo’s current bid to join Interpol.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-25T14:44:11.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989577/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989577/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-17","Kosovo: Recognition of States","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure that Kosovo receives universal recognition as a state ten years on from that country gaining independence.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","180681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989578","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>Normalising relations between Serbia and Kosovo is crucial for the security, stability and prosperity of both countries and the wider region. The Government believes that this should be on the basis of the recognition of independent sovereign states within their current borders. We believe that calls for re-drawing national borders could be de-stabilising in Kosovo, Serbia and beyond. We continue to support the EU-facilitated dialogue with a view to establishing a comprehensive and sustainable solution that benefits both countries.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-25T14:49:31.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989578/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989578/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-17","Kosovo: Serbia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether a land swap between Serbia and Kosovo will set a precedent for the territories in that region.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","180682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989579","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Department has regular conversations with health and social care providers and users as well as with the devolved administrations to ensure an exit is delivered which works for the health and social care sector throughout the entire United Kingdom.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-10-24T12:57:15.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989579/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989579/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Health Services: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether he has consulted people who require health and social care services on the impact on those sectors (a) throughout the UK and (b) in each of the four nations of the UK of leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","180762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989580","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>Normalising relations between Serbia and Kosovo is crucial for the security, stability and prosperity of both countries and the wider region. The Government believes that this should be on the basis of the recognition of independent sovereign states within their current borders. We believe that calls for re-drawing national borders could be de-stabilising in Kosovo, Serbia and beyond. We continue to support the EU-facilitated dialogue with a view to establishing a comprehensive and sustainable solution that benefits both countries.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-25T14:51:15.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989580/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989580/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-17","Kosovo: Serbia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether a land swap between Serbia and Kosovo would have the effect of improve relations between those countries.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","180683"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989581","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Department has regular conversations with health and social care organisations such as charities and patient advocacy groups as well as with the devolved administrations to ensure an exit is delivered which works for the health and social care sector throughout the entire United Kingdom.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-10-24T12:56:05.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989581/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989581/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Health Services: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department consulted organisations working for and on behalf of individuals who require health and social care services on the effect on those sectors (a) throughout the UK and (b) in each of the four nations of the UK of leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","180763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989582","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>Normalising relations between Serbia and Kosovo is crucial for the security, stability and prosperity of both countries and the wider region. The Government believes that this should be on the basis of the recognition of independent sovereign states within their current borders. We believe that calls for re-drawing national borders could be de-stabilising in Kosovo, Serbia and beyond. We continue to support the EU-facilitated dialogue with a view to establishing a comprehensive and sustainable solution that benefits both countries.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-25T14:53:09.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989582/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989582/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-17","Kosovo: Serbia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department’s policy is on potential land swaps between Serbia and Kosovo; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","180684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989583","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Government supports the integration of health and care services and recognises the good work being done by the Hinckley and Bosworth Wellbeing Partnership by taking a multi-agency approach to increase the wellbeing of people and to support them to live independently in their own homes for longer. Officials will be in contact with the Health and Wellbeing Board to understand more about the work being done.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-10-25T11:39:50.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989583/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989583/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","Health Services: Hinckley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will visit Hinckley to discuss the Hinckley and Bosworth Health and Wellbeing Partnership strategy of empowering people to manage their own physical and mental needs closer to home.","false","Biography information for David Tredinnick","Bosworth","David Tredinnick","180640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989584","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>NHS Digital publishes Hospital and Community Health Services (HCHS) workforce statistics for England. These include staff working in hospital trusts and clinical commissioning groups, but not staff working in primary care or in general practitioner surgeries, local authorities or other providers.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of non-United Kingdom European Union nationals that are employed in the NHS in England as at 30 September in the past two years and latest month available.</p><p> </p><p>The number of non-UK EU nationals increased by 4,367 (5.5%) between Sept 2016 and June 2018.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>September 2016</p></td><td><p>September 2017</p></td><td><p>30 June 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of other EU nationals employed by the NHS (headcount)</p></td><td><p>59,796</p></td><td><p>61,974</p></td><td><p>63,065</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br>Source: NHS Digital Quarterly HCHS workforce statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland is a matter for the devolved governments.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","180765","2018-10-24T12:53:25.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989584/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989584/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","NHS: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many nationals from other EU countries are employed in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","180764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989585","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-10-23","<p>The existing legal framework for the EU’s School Scheme is being rolled over into UK law under the European Union (Withdrawal) Act 2018. This provides a suitable basis to support future decisions on the longer term approach to school milk rather than include the arrangements in the Agriculture Bill.</p><p> </p><p>We want children to be healthy and well-nourished and regular dairy consumption makes an important contribution to this. The Government is also promoting children’s dairy consumption through, for example, the national free Nursery Milk Scheme, and by ensuring the availability of milk for pupils under the School Food Standards, including free milk for disadvantaged pupils.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-10-23T15:28:52.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989585/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989585/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-17","Schools: Nutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to replace the EU school fruit, vegetables and milk scheme; and for what reason such steps were not included in the Agriculture Bill.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","180649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989586","Home Office","false","2018-10-26","<p>The Home Office does not collect this information centrally. However, the most recent assessment of the evidence is available on GOV.UK: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/748140/hate-crime-a-thematic-review-of-the-current-evidence-oct2018-horr102.pdf." target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/748140/hate-crime-a-thematic-review-of-the-current-evidence-oct2018-horr102.pdf.</a></p><p>A joint Department for Digital, Culture, Media &amp; Sport and Home Office White Paper will be published this winter, which will set out a range of legislative and non-legislative measures detailing how we will tackle online harms. Potential areas where we will consider legislating include transparency report-ing to outline the response and prevalence of harms, including hate crime, on online platforms.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-10-26T13:44:39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989586/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989586/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-17","Hate Crime: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information his Department holds on the online platforms that hate crime offences have been perpetrated on.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","180738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989587","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>NHS Digital publishes Hospital and Community Health Services (HCHS) workforce statistics for England. These include staff working in hospital trusts and clinical commissioning groups, but not staff working in primary care or in general practitioner surgeries, local authorities or other providers.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of non-United Kingdom European Union nationals that are employed in the NHS in England as at 30 September in the past two years and latest month available.</p><p> </p><p>The number of non-UK EU nationals increased by 4,367 (5.5%) between Sept 2016 and June 2018.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>September 2016</p></td><td><p>September 2017</p></td><td><p>30 June 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of other EU nationals employed by the NHS (headcount)</p></td><td><p>59,796</p></td><td><p>61,974</p></td><td><p>63,065</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br>Source: NHS Digital Quarterly HCHS workforce statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland is a matter for the devolved governments.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","180764","2018-10-24T12:53:25.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989587/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989587/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","NHS: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what change there has been in the number of nationals from other EU countries working in the NHS in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","180765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989588","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-10-23","<p>As stated in my response to question 178290, the Government remains confident of having a functioning statute book in place by exit day whatever the outcome of negotiations. We expect a significant increase to the rate that these are laid over the coming months.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2018-10-23T16:45:05.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989588/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989588/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-10-17","Delegated Legislation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2018 to Question 178290 on Delegated Legislation, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the rate at which each Department is laying statutory instruments on EU exit domestic preparedness compared with the rate required to deliver a functioning statute book on the day that the UK leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","180722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989589","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-24","<p>The Government’s no-deal European Union exit contingency planning covers the entire United Kingdom and has been developed in partnership with the devolved administrations and local National Health Service colleagues. The Department will continue to work closely with colleagues in the devolved administrations towards achieving our objective of ensuring a seamless supply to patients throughout the UK should we leave the EU without a deal next March, to ensure a UK-wide, cross-Government approach to our planning.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier this year, the Department undertook an analysis using Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency and European Medicines Agency data on the supply chain for all medicines. This identified those products coming to the UK from or via the EU or wider EEA countries. We wrote to pharmaceutical companies on 23 August setting out our contingency planning and our aim of ensuring continuity of medicines supple for patients across the UK. We have received very good engagement from the industry in response to our letters. The Department continues to work closely with these companies to ensure that their UK stockpiles of medicines are sufficient to cope with any potential delays at the border that may arise in event of a no-deal EU exit.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","180767","2018-10-24T12:45:59.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989589/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/989589/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-17","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking with Ministers in each of the devolved administrations to ensure the adequacy of supply of medicines throughout the UK after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","180766"
