"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988802","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-10-24","<p>In response to the Taylor Review, Government has committed to publish a final list of quality of work measures and a baseline assessment of quality of work currently in the UK economy.</p><p> </p><p>We welcome the Carnegie Trust’s report, published on 7th September, as a valuable input to this work. We are currently considering their recommendations and will respond in due course. As part of this, BEIS officials are engaging with ONS to understand whether and how the Carnegie Trust’s recommendations could be implemented in practice.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","180226 ; 180227 ; 180229","2018-10-24T16:43:57.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988802/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988802/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988802/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-16","Employment: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2018 to Question 170362 on Employment, what steps he has taken to develop a minimum job quality standard.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","180228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988803","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-10-24","<p>In response to the Taylor Review, Government has committed to publish a final list of quality of work measures and a baseline assessment of quality of work currently in the UK economy.</p><p> </p><p>We welcome the Carnegie Trust’s report, published on 7th September, as a valuable input to this work. We are currently considering their recommendations and will respond in due course. As part of this, BEIS officials are engaging with ONS to understand whether and how the Carnegie Trust’s recommendations could be implemented in practice.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst","180226 ; 180227 ; 180228","2018-10-24T16:43:57.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988803/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988803/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988803/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-16","Employment: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2018 to Question 170362 on Employment, if he will establish an implementation group to support and advise on the delivery and development of the recommendations and proposals set out in the Carnegie Trust report referenced in his Answer.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","180229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988804","Department for Education","false","2018-10-24","<p>The attached table provides information for the full-time equivalent number of teachers and teaching assistants in service in state-funded nursery and primary schools in each parliamentary constituency within Cheshire West and Chester local authority, as well as in England, from November 2010 to November 2017.</p><p>Comparable figures for parliamentary constituency and phase are only available for teaching assistants and teacher numbers from November 2010, when the annual ‘School Workforce Census’ was introduced. [1]</p><p>The figures provided are publicly available in the underlying data files in the publication ‘School Workforce in England’. This is available at the following web link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-workforce" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-school-workforce</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The parliamentary constituencies provided are those that cover Cheshire West and Chester local authority. The schools in those constituencies that fall under Chester East and Halton local authorities have not been included in the figures.</p><p> </p><p>[1] The previous source was the ‘Form616g’ survey, which was based at local authority level only.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","180231","2018-10-24T15:34:58.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988804/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988804/answer","180230_180231_FTE_teachers_primary_Cheshire_West_Chester.xlsx","180230_180231_FTE_teachers_primary_Cheshire_West_C","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/988804/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-16","Teachers: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many teachers were employed in primary schools in each parliamentary constituency in Cheshire West and Chester in each of the last 1